@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About | Chapel Hill .NET</PageTitle>

<section class="page-hero">
    <div class="hero-card hero-card--about">
        <div class="hero-card__grid">
            <div class="hero-card__content">
                <span class="eyebrow eyebrow--light">About the community</span>
                <h1 class="hero-card__title">A meetup built around useful sessions and durable local connections.</h1>
                <p class="hero-card__lede">
                    Chapel Hill .NET exists to create a consistent place for developers to learn together, compare notes,
                    and stay sharp across the Microsoft ecosystem and the practical tooling around it.
                </p>
            </div>

            <aside class="hero-spotlight">
                <p class="hero-spotlight__label">What to expect</p>
                <h2>Clear topics, approachable formats, and a local point of view.</h2>
                <ul class="hero-spotlight__list">
                    <li>Sessions grounded in real engineering work.</li>
                    <li>Plenty of room for questions and follow-up discussion.</li>
                    <li>An environment that welcomes newcomers without flattening the technical depth.</li>
                </ul>
            </aside>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="page-section">
    <div class="page-shell story-grid">
        <article class="section-card story-panel">
            <span class="eyebrow">Our mission</span>
            <h2 class="section-title">Help local developers learn faster and build with more confidence.</h2>
            <p class="section-lede">
                We organize meetups, working sessions, and practical talks that help people understand the tradeoffs behind
                modern application development on .NET and Azure.
            </p>
            <p class="story-copy">
                The goal is not to chase hype. It is to surface what is actually useful: architecture lessons, platform
                decisions, debugging stories, deployment patterns, and the small implementation details that make a project
                better over time.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="section-card story-panel">
            <span class="eyebrow">How we operate</span>
            <h2 class="section-title">A community format that favors substance over noise.</h2>
            <div class="value-grid">
                <div class="value-card">
                    <h3>Practical first</h3>
                    <p>Talks and demos should leave people with ideas they can use next week.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="value-card">
                    <h3>Locally grounded</h3>
                    <p>The group is meant to connect people who can keep the conversation going after the event.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="value-card">
                    <h3>Technically honest</h3>
                    <p>We prefer clear tradeoffs and real constraints over polished but shallow answers.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="page-section page-section--muted">
    <div class="page-shell">
        <div class="section-heading">
            <div class="section-heading__content">
                <span class="eyebrow">What we cover</span>
                <h2 class="section-title">Breadth where it helps, depth where it matters.</h2>
                <p class="section-lede">
                    The agenda centers on the Microsoft stack, but the conversation is broader whenever broader tools help teams work better.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="topic-grid">
            <article class="section-card topic-card">
                <h3>Application engineering</h3>
                <ul class="story-list">
                    <li>C#, ASP.NET Core, Blazor, and service design</li>
                    <li>Testing, maintainability, and architectural tradeoffs</li>
                    <li>Performance, accessibility, and front-end quality</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="section-card topic-card">
                <h3>Cloud and delivery</h3>
                <ul class="story-list">
                    <li>Azure hosting, identity, observability, and operations</li>
                    <li>CI/CD pipelines, release safety, and platform patterns</li>
                    <li>Infrastructure decisions that hold up as teams grow</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="section-card topic-card">
                <h3>Developer workflow</h3>
                <ul class="story-list">
                    <li>Automation, scripting, and day-to-day productivity</li>
                    <li>AI-assisted development used with engineering discipline</li>
                    <li>Tooling choices that reduce friction instead of adding it</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="page-section">
    <div class="page-shell">
        <div class="cta-panel">
            <div>
                <span class="eyebrow">Join the community</span>
                <h2 class="section-title">Whether you are deep in production systems or just getting started, there is a place for you here.</h2>
                <p class="section-lede">
                    Show up for an event, bring a question, or propose a topic you want to unpack with other local developers.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="cta-panel__actions">
                <a class="site-button site-button--primary" href="/events">See upcoming sessions</a>
                <a class="site-button site-button--secondary" href="/#organizers">Meet the organizers</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
